nodes.title:
{
  "description": "The taxation crisis began with the Stamp Act of 1765, which colonial leaders viewed as a violation of their rights as Englishmen, triggering widespread discontent and a rallying cry for 'no taxation without representation.'",
  "type": "triggering",
  "date": "1765",
  "certainty": 1.0
}

{
  "description": "Colonial leaders, unified by the principle of 'no taxation without representation,' organized effective resistance against British policies through the formation of committees of correspondence and the implementation of economic boycotts.",
  "type": "intermediate",
  "certainty": 1.0
}

{
  "description": "George Washington's strategic decision to carefully avoid major decisive battles while concurrently building and preserving colonial military capacity enabled the Continental Army to effectively survive British campaigns throughout the extended conflict.",
  "type": "intermediate",
  "certainty": 1.0
}

{
  "description": "A crucial alliance with France was successfully negotiated by diplomatic leaders like Benjamin Franklin, which subsequently provided indispensable military and financial support to the American cause during the Revolutionary War.",
  "type": "intermediate",
  "certainty": 1.0
}

{
  "description": "The American Revolution of 1776 culminated in the successful achievement of colonial independence from British rule, fundamentally driven by effective revolutionary leadership that mobilized a unified opposition.",
  "type": "outcome",
  "date": "1776",
  "certainty": 1.0
}

{
  "description": "The emergence of effective revolutionary leadership, exemplified by figures like George Washington, John Adams, and Thomas Jefferson, was the fundamental driver that successfully transformed scattered colonial grievances into a unified independence movement and sustained the American Revolution for eight years.",
  "status": "supported",
  "certainty": 0.9
}

{
  "description": "Economic grievances or external pressures alone were sufficient and primary drivers of the American Revolution, capable of accounting for the organizational capacity and sustained effort required to achieve colonial independence.",
  "status": "refuted",
  "certainty": 0.9
}

